<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-07-15T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-07-15T19:00:00-05:00" n="429" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d429">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94119/651a: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-15T20:00:00-04:00">July 15, 1940—8
                                    p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>269. At the press conference on July 15 a correspondent asked whether
                                this Government had been informed of the news that the British are
                                working actively for settlement of the Sino-Japanese conflict. The
                                Secretary replied that we continue to pursue our policy of following
                                our own, separate, independent course with respect to the situation
                                in the Far East and added that, in order to know more fully what the
                                British are doing, the correspondent would want to speak to the
                                British themselves.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>